reate" and "father" of English verse. Chaucer appears throughout the fifteenth century as an adviser to kings and master of technique, and Lerer reveals the patterns of subjection, childishness, and inability that characterize the stance of Chaucer's imitators and his readers. In figures from the Canterbury Tales such as the abused Clerk, the boyish Squire, and the infantilized narrator of the "Tale of Sir Thopas," in the excuse-ridden narrator of Troilus and Criseyde, and in Chaucer's cursed Adam Scriveyn, the poet's inheritors found their oppressed personae. Through close readings of poetry from Lydgate to Skelton, detailed analysis of manuscript anthologies and early printed books, and inquiries into the political environments and the social contexts of bookmaking, Lerer charts the construction of a Chaucer unassailable in rhetorical prowess and political sanction, a Chaucer aureate and laureate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAesthetics, Medieval. 0aAuthors and readerszEnglandxHistory. 0aBooks and readingzEnglandxHistory. 0aEnglish poetryyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aReader-response criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBlake, Norman F.  aBoccaccio, Giovanni.  aBoffey, Julia.  aCaxton, William.  aDinshaw, Carolyn.  aEdwards, A.S.G.  aFisher, John Hurt.  aFradenburg, Louise.  aGower, John.  aHawes, Stephen.  aJean of Angoulême.  aKelly, Henry A.  aKipling, Gordon.  aLydgate, John.  aMaydiston, Richard.  aMiddleton, Anne.  aNorton-Smith, John.  aOvid.  aParkes, Malcolm B.  aPatterson, Lee.  aPynson, Robert.  aRobbins, Rossell Hope.  aScattergood, John.  aShirley, John.  aSquire, figure of the.  aTollemache, Lionel III.  aVirgil.  aWilson, Edward.  aYeager, Rob